
[1]slur

   SLUR, v.t.

   1. To soil; to sully; to contaminate; to disgrace.

   2. To pass lightly; to conceal. With periods, points and tropes he
   slurs his crimes.

   3. To cheat; to trick. [Unusual.]

   4. In music, to sing or perform in a smooth gliding style.

                                  SLUR, n.

   1. Properly, a black mark; hence, slight reproach or disgrace. Every
   violation of moral duty should be a slur to the reputation.

   2. In music, a mark connecting noest that are to be sung to the same
   syllable, or made in one continued breath of a wind instrument, or with
   one stoke of a stringed instrument.
